solution.p:
Use the substitution u=\tan x, so that \dee{u}=\sec^2 x\,\dee{x}:


\int\sec^4x\,\tan^{46}x\,\dee{x}
&=\int(\tan^2x+1) \tan^{46}x\, \sec^2 x\,\dee{x} 

&=\int (u^2+1)u^{46}\,\dee{u}
=\frac{u^{49}}{49}+\frac{u^{47}}{47}+C

&=\frac{\tan^{49}x}{49}+\frac{\tan^{47}x}{47}+C

We use the substitution u=\sec x, \dee{u} = \sec x \tan x \dee{x}. Then \tan^2 x = \sec^2 x - 1 = u^2-1.


\int \tan^3 x \sec^{1.5} x  \dee{x} &= \int \tan^2 x \cdot \sec^{0.5}x \cdot \sec x \tan x \dee{x}

&=\int(u^2-1)u^{0.5} \dee{u} = \int \left(u^{2.5} - u^{0.5}\right) \dee{u}

&=\frac{u^{3.5}}{3.5} - \frac{u^{1.5}}{1.5}+C

&=\frac{1}{3.5}\sec^{3.5}x - \frac{1}{1.5}\sec^{1.5}x+C


Note this solution used the same method as Example for the case that the power of tangent is odd and there is at least one secant.

We'll give two solutions.
Solution 1: As in Question, we have an odd power of tangent and at least one secant. So, as in strategy (2) of Section, we can use the substitution u=\sec x, \dee{u}=\sec x \tan x \dee{x}, and \tan^2 x = \sec^2 x -1=u^2-1.
\int \tan^3x\sec^2x \dee{x}&=\int \tan^2 x \sec x \cdot \sec x \tan x \dee{x}
&=\int(u^2-1)u \dee{u} = \int \left(u^3-u\right) \dee{u}
&=\frac{1}{4}u^4 - \frac{1}{2}u^2+C
&=\frac{1}{4}\sec^4 x - \frac{1}{2}\sec^2 x +C
Solution 2: We have an even, strictly positve, power of \sec x. So, as in strategy (3) of Section, we can use the substitution u=\tan x, \dee{u}=\sec^2 x~\dee{x}.
\int \tan^3x\sec^2x~\dee{x}\amp=\int \tan^3 x \cdot \sec^2 x ~\dee{x}
\amp=\int u^3~\dee{u}
\amp=\frac{1}{4}u^4 + C
\amp=\frac{1}{4}\tan^4x +C
It looks like we have two different answers. But, because \tan^2x = \sec^2 x-1,
\frac{1}{4}\tan^4 = \frac{1}{4} {(\sec^2x -1)}^2 = \frac{1}{4} \sec^4 x - \frac{1}{2}\sec^2 x + \frac{1}{4}
and the two answers are really the same, except that the arbitrary constant C of Solution1 is \frac{1}{4} plus the arbitrary constant C of Solution2.

